<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1445,1711]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,1445,1471]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Tube thick-walled, smooth, with a longitudinal sinuous ridge. Opercular peduncle smooth. Operculum radially or slightly bilaterally symmetrical, with bulbous proximal part and rounded to inverted saucerlike distal plate (
<figureCitation box="[351,485,1525,1551]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="31.[151,255,1685,1709]" captionTargetBox="[304,1278,209,1644]" captionTargetId="figure-180@31.[302,1286,194,1669]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 7. A: Josephella marenzelleri, from Mediterranean. A, Operculum. B–D: Laminatubus alvini, from Ecuador. B–D, opercula, lateral view. D: collar chaetae. E–G: Placostegus californicus, from California, LACM-AHF 179, holotype. E–G, same operculum, left, right and apical views. H–J: Pomatoceros minutus, from Oaxaca, UMAR-Poly 79. H, tube. I–J, same operculum, dorsal and lateral views. K–M: Pomatoceros minutus, from Hawaii, UMAR-Poly 73. K, operculum, lateral view. L–M, other operculum, dorsal and lateral views. N: Pomatoleios kraussii from South Africa. N, Thorax and operculum, dorsal view. O: Pomatoleios kraussii from Madagascar. O, operculum shows the talon, lateral view. P–R: Pomatoleios sp. from Pacific of Panama, UMAR-Poly 81. P–Q, same operculum, dorsal and lateral views. R, other operculum shows the talon, dorsal view. S: Pomatostegus stellatus, from Baja California Sur, UMAR-Poly 82. R, operculum, lateral view. (Fig. A, redrawn from Zibrowius, 1968. Figs B–D, redrawn from ten Hove &amp; Zibrowius, 1986. Fig. N, redrawn from Day, 1967. Fig. O, redrawn from ten Hove, 1973)." pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Figs 7B–C</figureCitation>
). Thoracic membrane extends to second chaetiger. Collar with “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Blainville" authorityYear="1818" box="[1251,1426,1525,1551]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Spirobranchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">Spirobranchus</taxonomicName>
” chaetae, coarsely serrated in the subapical section (
<figureCitation box="[748,843,1565,1591]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="31.[151,255,1685,1709]" captionTargetBox="[304,1278,209,1644]" captionTargetId="figure-180@31.[302,1286,194,1669]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 7. A: Josephella marenzelleri, from Mediterranean. A, Operculum. B–D: Laminatubus alvini, from Ecuador. B–D, opercula, lateral view. D: collar chaetae. E–G: Placostegus californicus, from California, LACM-AHF 179, holotype. E–G, same operculum, left, right and apical views. H–J: Pomatoceros minutus, from Oaxaca, UMAR-Poly 79. H, tube. I–J, same operculum, dorsal and lateral views. K–M: Pomatoceros minutus, from Hawaii, UMAR-Poly 73. K, operculum, lateral view. L–M, other operculum, dorsal and lateral views. N: Pomatoleios kraussii from South Africa. N, Thorax and operculum, dorsal view. O: Pomatoleios kraussii from Madagascar. O, operculum shows the talon, lateral view. P–R: Pomatoleios sp. from Pacific of Panama, UMAR-Poly 81. P–Q, same operculum, dorsal and lateral views. R, other operculum shows the talon, dorsal view. S: Pomatostegus stellatus, from Baja California Sur, UMAR-Poly 82. R, operculum, lateral view. (Fig. A, redrawn from Zibrowius, 1968. Figs B–D, redrawn from ten Hove &amp; Zibrowius, 1986. Fig. N, redrawn from Day, 1967. Fig. O, redrawn from ten Hove, 1973)." pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 7D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1445,1711]" box="[198,916,1605,1631]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,301,1605,1631]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Habitat.</emphasis>
